        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3508288951" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14417286565753594042">This book. You guys. The final page had me sobbing and ready to vomit all at the same time. <br/><br/>This is the story of Thomas Jefferson&apos;s children that he had with his slave Sally Hemmings. It is told from 3 different points of view starting with Hemmings&apos;s oldest son, then moving to one of her younger sons, then to another slave boy who lived with them at Monticello. Through this story we see the children&apos;s struggle with wanting to be loved by a father who &quot;owns&quot; them and their community. We also see</span>
  <span id="freeText14417286565753594042" style="display:none">This book. You guys. The final page had me sobbing and ready to vomit all at the same time. <br /><br />This is the story of Thomas Jefferson's children that he had with his slave Sally Hemmings. It is told from 3 different points of view starting with Hemmings's oldest son, then moving to one of her younger sons, then to another slave boy who lived with them at Monticello. Through this story we see the children's struggle with wanting to be loved by a father who "owns" them and their community. We also see the fear that arises in the slave community as Jefferson ages and they wonder what will happen to them upon his death. This book had so much good information in it for middle school readers and even adults. I personally learned so many new things I had no knowledge of before. I'm just so grateful for this book and the message it puts into the hands of each of its readers.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14417286565753594042" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


